MetAlyzer User Guide

Nils Mechtel & Carolin Andresen

2022-01-24

The package provides methods to read output files from the MetIDQâ„¢ software into R. Metabolomics data is read and reformatted into an S4 object for convenient data handling, statistics and downstream analysis.

Install

There is a version available on CRAN.

install.packages("MetAlyzer")

Overview

The package takes metabolomic measurements as â€œ.xlsxâ€ files generated from the MetIDQâ„¢ software. Additionally, meta data for each sample can be provided for further analysis.

Effective quantification of metabolites requires a reliable signal. The limit of detection (LOD) is defined as 3 times signal-to-noise of the baseline, calculated by the software MetIDQ for each metabolite. Values are classified as â€œValidâ€, â€œLOQâ€ (below limit of quantification) or â€œLODâ€ (below limit of detection). This information is encoded in the color in the â€œ.xlsxâ€ table. Further color codes can include â€œISTD Out of Rangeâ€, â€œInvalidâ€ and â€œIncompleteâ€. The MetAlyzer packages allow to read both information, the value and the quantification status, gives statistics about the quantification efficacy and allows filtering based on the LOD.

Example of excel sheet.

Get started

To present the functionalities of the package, we use a data set published by Gegner et al. 2022. This data set used 6 (1 to 6) different extraction methods to quantify 630 metabolites in triplicates for 4 tissue types (Drosophila, Mouse Liver, Mouse Kidney, Zebrafish Liver).

Set data paths to the example data and a meta data file:

fpath <- system.file("extdata", "example_data.xlsx", package = "MetAlyzer")
mpath <- system.file("extdata", "example_meta_data.rds", package = "MetAlyzer")

Initialize MetAlyzer object and load data:

obj <- MetAlyzerDataset(file_path = fpath)
show(obj)
#> -------------------------------------
#> File name: example_data.xlsx 
#> Sheet: 1 
#> File path: /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/4.0/Resources/library/MetAlyzer/extdata 
#> Metabolites: 862 
#> Classes: 24 
#> Including metabolism indicators: TRUE 
#> Number of samples: 74 
#> Columns meta data: "Plate Bar Code"; "Sample Bar Code"; "Sample Type"; "Group"; "Tissue"; "Sample Volume"; "Measurement Time"
#> Ploting data created: FALSE

The overview shows the different slots in the MetAlyzer object. The 630 metabolites are accompanied by 232 metabolite indicators calculated by the MetIDQâ„¢ software.

The slots can be accessed using the functions metaData, rawData, quantStatus and metabolites.

For example:

head(metaData(obj))

Filter metabolites and meta data

To subset the data set, the functions filterMetabolites and filterMetaData can be used to filter for certain metabolite classes or meta data. The original data are kept, so the filtering can be reset to the original data set using resetMetabolites and resetMetaData.

For example, we want to exclude the metabolite indicators:

obj <- filterMetabolites(obj, class_name = "Metabolism Indicators")
#> 232 metabolites were filtered!

There are also 2 blank samples in the data that we want to remove: The extraction methods are encoded in the column â€œGroupâ€ of the meta data. We only keep those samples that are named c(1:6).

obj <- filterMetaData(obj, column = Group, keep = c(1:6))

Show statistics

The function summariseQuantData shows a summary of the quantification statistics of the data set. E.g. 45.36% of the metabolites across the data set were below the LOD.

summariseQuantData(obj)
#> -------------------------------------
#> Valid: 21951 (48.39%)
#> LOQ: 2832 (6.24%)
#> LOD: 20577 (45.36%)
#> NAs: 0 (0%)

Add meta data

As the different extraction methods were measured in triplicates, we want to add this meta data using the function updateMetaData. First we load the meta data.

meta_df <- readRDS(mpath)
head(meta_df)
#>   Method Replicate
#> 1      1        R1
#> 2      1        R2
#> 3      1        R3
#> 4      2        R1
#> 5      2        R2
#> 6      2        R3

And then add the replicate information.

obj <- updateMetaData(obj, name = Replicate, new_colum = meta_df$Replicate)
show(obj)
#> -------------------------------------
#> File name: example_data.xlsx 
#> Sheet: 1 
#> File path: /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/4.0/Resources/library/MetAlyzer/extdata 
#> Metabolites: 630 
#> Classes: 23 
#> Including metabolism indicators: FALSE 
#> Number of samples: 72 
#> Columns meta data: "Plate Bar Code"; "Sample Bar Code"; "Sample Type"; "Group"; "Tissue"; "Sample Volume"; "Measurement Time"; "name"
#> Ploting data created: FALSE

Rename meta data

In the meta data, the description of the 6 extraction methods is encoded in the column â€œGroupâ€. For downstream analyses, we want to rename this column into â€œMethodâ€ using renameMetaData.

obj <- renameMetaData(obj, Method = Group)
head(metaData(obj))
#> -------------------------------------
#> Returning filtered meta data

Reformat for plotting

For further filtering and plotting, the data can be reformatted into a data frame. This allows easy plotting with e.g.Â ggplot2 and filtering for e.g.Â metabolites of interest or the quantification status. If replicates are available, some statistics is automatically calculated. For our study we can add the â€œMethodâ€ and â€œTissueâ€ to indicate there are replicates for these variables.

obj <- createPlottingData(obj, Method, Tissue)
gg_df <- plottingData(obj)

head(gg_df)
#> # A tibble: 6 Ã— 12
#> # Groups:   Method, Tissue, Metabolite [2]
#>   Method Tissue     Metabolite Class  Replicates Concentration  Mean    SD    CV
#>   <fct>  <fct>      <fct>      <fct>       <int>         <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
#> 1 1      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          1         203    179.  82.4 0.461
#> 2 1      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          2          86.8  179.  82.4 0.461
#> 3 1      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          3         246    179.  82.4 0.461
#> 4 2      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          1         198    231. 124.  0.538
#> 5 2      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          2         369    231. 124.  0.538
#> 6 2      Drosophila C0         Acylcâ€¦          3         127    231. 124.  0.538
#> # â€¦ with 3 more variables: CV_thresh <fct>, Status <fct>,
#> #   valid_replicates <lgl>

For example, we can filter for glutamic acid (Glu) and plot the concentration.

glu_gg_df <- filter(gg_df, Metabolite == "Glu")

ggplot(glu_gg_df, aes(Method, Concentration, color = Status)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Valid" = "#00CD66",
                                "LOQ" = "#87CEEB",
                                "LOD" = "#6A5ACD")) + 
  ylab("Concentration [pmol/mg Tissue]") + 
  facet_grid(~ Tissue)

Imputation and transformation

In case NAs or zeros are produced, we provide zero imputation as described in (Gegner et al.). Before, the imputation, there are 12,212 zero values in the data set.

length(which(gg_df$Concentration == 0))
#> [1] 12212

Now we impute the data for each tissue separately.

obj <- imputePlottingData(obj, Tissue)
imp_gg_df <- plottingData(obj)

After the imputation, the lowest values is non-zero. The imputation can additionally be performed for each metabolite separately (recommended), which we do not show for simplicity since some metabolites only show zero values. The imputed values are written into column â€œimp_Concâ€.

min(imp_gg_df$imp_Conc)
#> [1] 2e-04

Raw or imputed concentrations in the object can directly be transformed using the function transformPlottingData. By default the data is log2 transformed and written into the column â€œtransf_Concâ€.

obj <- transformPlottingData(obj)
trans_gg_df <- plottingData(obj)
head(trans_gg_df)
#> # A tibble: 6 Ã— 14
#> # Groups:   Method, Tissue, Metabolite [2]
#>   Method Tissue  Metabolite Class  Replicates Concentration imp_Conc transf_Conc
#>   <fct>  <fct>   <fct>      <fct>       <int>         <dbl>    <dbl>       <dbl>
#> 1 1      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          1         203      203          7.67
#> 2 1      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          2          86.8     86.8        6.44
#> 3 1      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          3         246      246          7.94
#> 4 2      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          1         198      198          7.63
#> 5 2      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          2         369      369          8.53
#> 6 2      Drosopâ€¦ C0         Acylcâ€¦          3         127      127          6.99
#> # â€¦ with 6 more variables: Mean <dbl>, SD <dbl>, CV <dbl>, CV_thresh <fct>,
#> #   Status <fct>, valid_replicates <lgl>

To plot imputed and transformed data, we filter again for glutamic acid:

trans_glu_gg_df <- filter(trans_gg_df, Metabolite == "Glu")

ggplot(trans_glu_gg_df, aes(Method, transf_Conc, color = Status)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Valid" = "#00CD66",
                                "LOQ" = "#87CEEB",
                                "LOD" = "#6A5ACD")) +
  facet_grid(~ Tissue)

ANOVA

As described in (Gegner et al.), an ANOVA can be used to identify metabolites which are significantly higher in one or more methods compared to all other for each metabolite.

obj <- performANOVA(obj, categorical = Method)
anv_gg_df <- plottingData(obj)
head(data.frame(anv_gg_df))
